
[1]derange

   DERANGE, v.t.

   1. To put out of order; to disturb the regular order of; to throw into
   confusion; as, to derange the plans of a commander, or the affairs of a
   nation.

   I had long supposed that nothing could derange or interrupt the course
   of putrefaction.

   2. To embarrass; to disorder; as, his private affairs are deranged.

   3. To disorder the intellect; to disturb the regular operations of
   reason.

   4. To remove from place or office, as the personal staff of a principal
   military officer. Thus when a general officer resigns or is removed
   from office, the personal staff appointed by himself are said to be
   deranged.
